    <section class="font-body text-on-surface leading-relaxed space-y-6">
      <p>Malaysia is one of Southeast Asia's leading producers and distributors of marble, granite, and ceramic tiles. From Selangor factories supplying domestic construction projects to exporters shipping to Singapore and beyond, the challenge is always the same: how do you move fragile, heavy stone and ceramic products without breakage? Honeycomb cardboard is the material increasingly solving this problem.</p>

      <p>At Quinocycle Sdn. Bhd. in Balakong, Selangor, we supply honeycomb cardboard panels to tile manufacturers, stone merchants, and logistics companies across the Klang Valley and Peninsular Malaysia. This guide explains how honeycomb cardboard works for stone and tile transport, what specifications to choose, and how to integrate it into your packing process.</p>

      <h2 class="font-headline text-2xl font-bold text-on-surface mt-10 mb-4">Why Stone and Tile Transport Needs Specialised Packaging</h2>
      <p>Marble and granite slabs are simultaneously very heavy and very brittle. A 20kg marble slab can shatter from a single sharp impact, and chips on finished edges reduce the value of a slab dramatically. Ceramic tiles are thinner and more uniform, but still prone to edge chipping and cracking when tiles in a pack shift and strike each other during transit vibration.</p>

      <h3 class="font-headline text-xl font-semibold text-on-surface mt-6 mb-3">The Vibration Problem in Road Transport</h3>
      <p>Malaysian road transport introduces continuous low-frequency vibration over the entire journey. Over a 2-hour truck trip from Selangor to Johor, a pallet of tiles experiences thousands of vibration cycles. Without damping material between tiles, small movements accumulate into significant relative displacement — and that is when edges chip and slabs crack. Honeycomb cardboard, placed between slabs or around tile bundles, absorbs and dissipates this vibrational energy effectively.</p>

      <h3 class="font-headline text-xl font-semibold text-on-surface mt-6 mb-3">Impact Events During Loading and Unloading</h3>
      <p>The highest risk moments are during forklift loading, pallet drops, and manual unloading. A pallet dropped from even 5cm onto a hard warehouse floor generates significant shock force. Honeycomb panels on the pallet base and as interleaving layers absorb this shock energy in a controlled way — the hexagonal cell structure compresses and distributes the load, rather than allowing it to transmit directly through the stone.</p>

      <h2 class="font-headline text-2xl font-bold text-on-surface mt-10 mb-4">How to Use Honeycomb Panels for Marble and Granite</h2>

      <div class="bg-surface-variant/50 border border-outline-variant/20 rounded-2xl p-6 my-8">
        <h3 class="font-headline text-lg font-bold text-on-surface mb-4">Honeycomb Panel Placement Guide for Stone Transport</h3>
        <div class="space-y-3 font-body text-sm">
          <div class="flex justify-between items-start py-2 border-b border-outline-variant/20">
            <span class="font-semibold text-on-surface">Between slabs</span>
            <span class="text-secondary text-right max-w-xs">15mm panel between each slab prevents surface-to-surface contact and vibration transfer</span>
          </div>
          <div class="flex justify-between items-start py-2 border-b border-outline-variant/20">
            <span class="font-semibold text-on-surface">Edge protection</span>
            <span class="text-secondary text-right max-w-xs">20–30mm folded panels along all four edges absorb lateral impact</span>
          </div>
          <div class="flex justify-between items-start py-2 border-b border-outline-variant/20">
            <span class="font-semibold text-on-surface">Pallet base layer</span>
            <span class="text-secondary text-right max-w-xs">25–40mm base panel distributes bottom slab load and absorbs pallet drop impact</span>
          </div>
          <div class="flex justify-between items-start py-2">
            <span class="font-semibold text-on-surface">Top cap panel</span>
            <span class="text-secondary text-right max-w-xs">Top honeycomb panel prevents damage from overhead strapping pressure</span>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <h2 class="font-headline text-2xl font-bold text-on-surface mt-10 mb-4">Honeycomb Cardboard for Ceramic Tile Packs</h2>
      <p>Ceramic and porcelain tiles are typically packed in paper or plastic-wrapped bundles before boxing. Adding a honeycomb cardboard interleaf between tiles (or between tile packs in a master carton) significantly reduces edge chipping. For export-grade packaging, wrapping each tile pack with a 5–10mm honeycomb panel before placing in the carton adds minimal cost but dramatically reduces breakage claims.</p>

      <h3 class="font-headline text-xl font-semibold text-on-surface mt-6 mb-3">Combining with Stretch Film</h3>
      <p>For stone slab bundles on A-frame racks, applying stretch film over honeycomb interleafs keeps the panels firmly in place during transit movement. The stretch film prevents panel migration while the honeycomb continues to provide cushioning. This combination is used by leading Malaysian tile exporters for shipments to the Middle East and East Asia.</p>

      <h2 class="font-headline text-2xl font-bold text-on-surface mt-10 mb-4">Cost Analysis: Honeycomb vs Traditional Packaging</h2>
      <p>Traditional stone packing uses wooden crates, sawdust, or polystyrene foam. Honeycomb cardboard competes strongly on both performance and cost. It is lighter than wood (reducing freight cost), more consistent than sawdust (no moisture or contamination risk), and more recyclable than foam. For exporters targeting sustainability-conscious markets, honeycomb packaging also supports ESG documentation.</p>

